Model Evaluation and Selection

Introduction

Model evaluation is a critical step in the machine learning workflow that determines how well your model performs on unseen data. In this lecture, we’ll explore comprehensive techniques for evaluating both regression and classification models, understanding various metrics, and learning how to select the best model for your business application.

Learning Objectives

By the end of this lecture, you will be able to:

  1. Understand and apply evaluation metrics for regression models
  2. Master classification metrics including confusion matrices, precision, recall, and F1-score
  3. Interpret ROC curves and AUC scores
  4. Compare multiple models systematically
  5. Understand cross-validation techniques
  6. Apply model selection strategies to business problems

Setup and Libraries

    confusion_matrix, classification_report, accuracy_score, 
    precision_score, recall_score, f1_score,
    roc_curve, auc, roc_auc_score

Part 1: Regression Model Evaluation

1.1 Key Regression Metrics

When evaluating regression models, we use several metrics to understand different aspects of model performance:

# Generate sample regression data
np.random.seed(42)
n_samples = 200

# Create features
X = np.random.randn(n_samples, 3)
# Create target with some noise
true_weights = [3, -2, 1.5]
y_true = X @ true_weights + np.random.randn(n_samples) * 2

# Split data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y_true, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Train model
reg_model = LinearRegression()
reg_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = reg_model.predict(X_test)

# Calculate metrics
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_test, y_pred)

print("Regression Model Evaluation Metrics:")
print("-" * 40)
print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE):     {mse:.4f}")
print(f"Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): {rmse:.4f}")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE):    {mae:.4f}")
print(f"R-squared (R²):               {r2:.4f}")
print(f"Mean Absolute Percentage Error: {mape:.2%}")
Regression Model Evaluation Metrics:
----------------------------------------
Mean Squared Error (MSE):     3.8662
Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): 1.9663
Mean Absolute Error (MAE):    1.5873
R-squared (R²):               0.7963
Mean Absolute Percentage Error: 140.06%

1.2 Understanding Each Metric

Regression Metrics Explained
  • MSE: Average squared difference between predicted and actual values. Penalizes large errors more.
  • RMSE: Square root of MSE, in the same units as the target variable.
  • MAE: Average absolute difference. Less sensitive to outliers than MSE.
  • R²: Proportion of variance explained by the model (0 to 1, higher is better).
  • MAPE: Average percentage error, useful for understanding relative error magnitude.

Part 2: Classification Model Evaluation

2.1 Confusion Matrix

The confusion matrix is the foundation for understanding classification performance:

# Generate sample classification data
from sklearn.datasets import make_classification

X_class, y_class = make_classification(
    n_samples=500, n_features=10, n_informative=5,
    n_redundant=3, n_classes=2, random_state=42,
    class_sep=1.0
)

# Split data
X_train_c, X_test_c, y_train_c, y_test_c = train_test_split(
    X_class, y_class, test_size=0.3, random_state=42
)

# Train logistic regression
clf = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
clf.fit(X_train_c, y_train_c)
y_pred_c = clf.predict(X_test_c)
y_pred_proba = clf.predict_proba(X_test_c)[:, 1]

# Create confusion matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test_c, y_pred_c)

# Visualize confusion matrix
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', 
            xticklabels=['Predicted 0', 'Predicted 1'],
            yticklabels=['Actual 0', 'Actual 1'])
plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
plt.ylabel('True Label')
plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')

# Add text annotations for TP, TN, FP, FN

plt.text(1.5, 0.1, 'False Positives', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10)
plt.text(0.5, 1.1, 'False Negatives', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10)
plt.text(1.5, 1.1, 'True Positives', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10)

plt.show()

2.3 Understanding Classification Metrics

Key Classification Metrics

Accuracy = (TP + TN) / Total - Overall correctness of the model - Can be misleading with imbalanced classes

Precision = TP / (TP + FP) - Of all positive predictions, how many were correct? - Important when false positives are costly

Recall (Sensitivity) = TP / (TP + FN) - Of all actual positives, how many did we identify? - Important when false negatives are costly

F1-Score = 2 × (Precision × Recall) / (Precision + Recall) - Harmonic mean of precision and recall - Good for imbalanced datasets

2.4 ROC Curve and AUC

# Calculate ROC curve
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test_c, y_pred_proba)
roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

# Plot ROC curve
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=2, 
         label=f'ROC curve (AUC = {roc_auc:.3f})')
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--', 
         label='Random Classifier')

# Add threshold annotations
for i in range(0, len(thresholds), len(thresholds)//5):
    plt.annotate(f'{thresholds[i]:.2f}', 
                xy=(fpr[i], tpr[i]), 
                xytext=(fpr[i]+0.05, tpr[i]-0.05),
                fontsize=8, alpha=0.7)

plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate (1 - Specificity)')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate (Sensitivity)')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.show()

print(f"Area Under the Curve (AUC): {roc_auc:.4f}")

2.5 Threshold Selection

# Analyze different thresholds
threshold_values = [0.3, 0.5, 0.7]
results = []

for threshold in threshold_values:
    y_pred_thresh = (y_pred_proba >= threshold).astype(int)
    acc = accuracy_score(y_test_c, y_pred_thresh)
    prec = precision_score(y_test_c, y_pred_thresh)
    rec = recall_score(y_test_c, y_pred_thresh)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test_c, y_pred_thresh)
    
    results.append({
        'Threshold': threshold,
        'Accuracy': acc,
        'Precision': prec,
        'Recall': rec,
        'F1-Score': f1
    })

results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)
print("Performance at Different Thresholds:")
print(results_df.to_string(index=False))

# Visualize threshold impact
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
x = np.arange(len(threshold_values))
width = 0.2

metrics = ['Accuracy', 'Precision', 'Recall', 'F1-Score']
colors = ['blue', 'green', 'red', 'purple']

for i, metric in enumerate(metrics):
    values = results_df[metric].values
    ax.bar(x + i * width, values, width, label=metric, color=colors[i], alpha=0.7)

ax.set_xlabel('Threshold')
ax.set_ylabel('Score')
ax.set_title('Classification Metrics at Different Thresholds')
ax.set_xticks(x + width * 1.5)
ax.set_xticklabels(threshold_values)
ax.legend()
ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.show()

Part 3: Cross-Validation

3.1 K-Fold Cross-Validation

Cross-validation provides a more robust estimate of model performance:

# Perform k-fold cross-validation for regression
kfold = KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

# Regression cross-validation
reg_cv_scores = cross_val_score(LinearRegression(), X, y_true, 
                                cv=kfold, scoring='r2')

print("Regression Model - 5-Fold Cross-Validation:")
print("-" * 40)
print(f"R² scores for each fold: {reg_cv_scores}")
print(f"Mean R² score: {reg_cv_scores.mean():.4f}")
print(f"Standard deviation: {reg_cv_scores.std():.4f}")
print(f"95% CI: [{reg_cv_scores.mean() - 2*reg_cv_scores.std():.4f}, "
      f"{reg_cv_scores.mean() + 2*reg_cv_scores.std():.4f}]")

# Classification cross-validation
clf_cv_scores = cross_val_score(LogisticRegression(random_state=42), 
                                X_class, y_class, 
                                cv=kfold, scoring='accuracy')

print("\nClassification Model - 5-Fold Cross-Validation:")
print("-" * 40)
print(f"Accuracy scores for each fold: {clf_cv_scores}")
print(f"Mean accuracy: {clf_cv_scores.mean():.4f}")
print(f"Standard deviation: {clf_cv_scores.std():.4f}")
print(f"95% CI: [{clf_cv_scores.mean() - 2*clf_cv_scores.std():.4f}, "
      f"{clf_cv_scores.mean() + 2*clf_cv_scores.std():.4f}]")

Part 4: Model Comparison

4.1 Comparing Multiple Models

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.svm import SVC

# Define models to compare
models = {
    'Logistic Regression': LogisticRegression(random_state=42),
    'Decision Tree': DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, max_depth=5),
    'Random Forest': RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42, n_estimators=100),
    'SVM': SVC(random_state=42, probability=True)
}

# Compare models
comparison_results = []

for name, model in models.items():
    # Train model
    model.fit(X_train_c, y_train_c)
    
    # Make predictions
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_c)
    y_pred_proba = model.predict_proba(X_test_c)[:, 1] if hasattr(model, 'predict_proba') else None
    
    # Calculate metrics
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test_c, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_test_c, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test_c, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test_c, y_pred)
    auc_score = roc_auc_score(y_test_c, y_pred_proba) if y_pred_proba is not None else None
    
    comparison_results.append({
        'Model': name,
        'Accuracy': accuracy,
        'Precision': precision,
        'Recall': recall,
        'F1-Score': f1,
        'AUC': auc_score
    })

# Create comparison dataframe
comparison_df = pd.DataFrame(comparison_results)
comparison_df = comparison_df.sort_values('F1-Score', ascending=False)

print("Model Comparison Results:")
print("-" * 60)
print(comparison_df.to_string(index=False))

Part 5: Business Context and Interpretation

5.1 Choosing Metrics for Business Problems

Different business problems require different evaluation priorities:

Business Context Examples

Credit Card Fraud Detection - Priority: Minimize false negatives (missing fraud) - Key Metric: Recall - Reasoning: Missing fraud is very costly

Email Spam Filtering - Priority: Balance precision and recall - Key Metric: F1-Score - Reasoning: Both spam in inbox and legitimate emails in spam are problematic

Customer Churn Prediction - Priority: Precision for targeted interventions - Key Metric: Precision - Reasoning: Retention campaigns are expensive, target likely churners

Medical Diagnosis - Priority: Minimize false negatives - Key Metric: Recall (Sensitivity) - Reasoning: Missing a disease can be life-threatening

5.2 Cost-Sensitive Evaluation

# Define costs for a business scenario (e.g., loan default prediction)
cost_matrix = {
    'True Negative': 0,      # Correctly approved good loan
    'False Positive': -500,  # Rejected good loan (lost profit)
    'False Negative': -5000, # Approved bad loan (default loss)
    'True Positive': 0       # Correctly rejected bad loan
}

# Calculate total cost for our confusion matrix
tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()

total_cost = (tn * cost_matrix['True Negative'] + 
              fp * cost_matrix['False Positive'] +
              fn * cost_matrix['False Negative'] + 
              tp * cost_matrix['True Positive'])

avg_cost_per_prediction = total_cost / len(y_test_c)

print("Cost-Sensitive Analysis:")
print("-" * 40)
print(f"True Negatives cost:  ${tn * cost_matrix['True Negative']:,}")
print(f"False Positives cost: ${fp * cost_matrix['False Positive']:,}")
print(f"False Negatives cost: ${fn * cost_matrix['False Negative']:,}")
print(f"True Positives cost:  ${tp * cost_matrix['True Positive']:,}")
print(f"\nTotal Cost: ${total_cost:,}")
print(f"Average Cost per Prediction: ${avg_cost_per_prediction:,.2f}")

Part 6: Advanced Topics

6.1 Handling Imbalanced Datasets

# Create imbalanced dataset
from sklearn.datasets import make_classification

X_imb, y_imb = make_classification(
    n_samples=1000, n_features=10, n_informative=5,
    n_redundant=3, n_classes=2, weights=[0.9, 0.1],
    random_state=42, class_sep=1.0
)

print("Class Distribution:")
print(pd.Series(y_imb).value_counts())
print(f"\nClass Balance: {pd.Series(y_imb).value_counts()[1] / len(y_imb):.1%} positive class")

# Compare metrics with and without class weighting
X_train_imb, X_test_imb, y_train_imb, y_test_imb = train_test_split(
    X_imb, y_imb, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y_imb
)

# Model without class weighting
clf_no_weight = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
clf_no_weight.fit(X_train_imb, y_train_imb)
y_pred_no_weight = clf_no_weight.predict(X_test_imb)

# Model with class weighting
clf_weighted = LogisticRegression(class_weight='balanced', random_state=42)
clf_weighted.fit(X_train_imb, y_train_imb)
y_pred_weighted = clf_weighted.predict(X_test_imb)

# Compare results
print("\nModel Performance Comparison:")
print("-" * 50)
print("Without Class Weighting:")
print(f"  Precision: {precision_score(y_test_imb, y_pred_no_weight):.3f}")
print(f"  Recall:    {recall_score(y_test_imb, y_pred_no_weight):.3f}")
print(f"  F1-Score:  {f1_score(y_test_imb, y_pred_no_weight):.3f}")

print("\nWith Class Weighting:")
print(f"  Precision: {precision_score(y_test_imb, y_pred_weighted):.3f}")
print(f"  Recall:    {recall_score(y_test_imb, y_pred_weighted):.3f}")
print(f"  F1-Score:  {f1_score(y_test_imb, y_pred_weighted):.3f}")

Summary and Best Practices

Key Takeaways

  1. No Single Metric is Perfect: Always use multiple metrics to evaluate your model
  2. Context Matters: Choose metrics based on your business problem
  3. Cross-Validation: Use it for robust performance estimates
  4. Visualization: Always visualize your results for better understanding
  5. Compare Multiple Models: Don’t settle for the first model that works

Model Selection Checklist

Model Selection Best Practices

✅ Define Success Metrics based on business requirements
✅ Use Cross-Validation for robust evaluation
✅ Check for Overfitting using train vs. test performance
✅ Consider Model Complexity vs. interpretability trade-offs
✅ Evaluate on Multiple Metrics not just accuracy
✅ Test on Hold-out Data for final validation
✅ Document Assumptions and limitations
✅ Consider Deployment Constraints (speed, memory, interpretability)

Common Pitfalls to Avoid

Common Mistakes

❌ Using accuracy as the only metric for imbalanced datasets
❌ Not checking for data leakage between train and test sets
❌ Ignoring business costs when selecting models
❌ Over-optimizing on a single metric
❌ Not considering model interpretability requirements
❌ Forgetting to scale features when comparing models

Try these exercises to reinforce your understanding:

  1. Load a dataset and compare at least 3 different models using appropriate metrics
  2. Create a custom scoring function that incorporates business costs
  3. Perform cross-validation and visualize the results
  4. Generate ROC curves for multiple models and interpret the results
  5. Handle an imbalanced dataset and compare different strategies
